The random variables \(X\) and \(Y\) are independent, with \(X \sim N(5, 16)\) and \(Y \sim N(6, 9)\). The probability \(P(X > Y)\) is equivalent to \(P(X - Y > 0)\).

Since \(X\) and \(Y\) are independent, the difference \(X - Y\) follows a normal distribution with mean \(\mu = \mu_X - \mu_Y = 5 - 6 = -1\) and variance \(\sigma^2 = \sigma_X^2 + \sigma_Y^2 = 16 + 9 = 25\). Thus, \(X - Y \sim N(-1, 25)\), and the standard deviation is \(\sigma = \sqrt{25} = 5\).

To find \(P(X - Y > 0)\), standardize the variable:  
\[
Z = \frac{(X - Y) - (-1)}{5} = \frac{X - Y + 1}{5}
\]  
Then, \(P(X - Y > 0) = P\left(Z > \frac{0 - (-1)}{5}\right) = P(Z > 0.2)\), where \(Z \sim N(0, 1)\).

Using the standard normal distribution, \(P(Z > 0.2) = 1 - P(Z \leq 0.2)\). From standard normal tables, \(P(Z \leq 0.2) \approx 0.5793\), so:  
\[
P(Z > 0.2) = 1 - 0.5793 = 0.4207
\]  
Rounded to three decimal places, this is 0.421.

The probability has no unit, and the value is rounded to three significant figures for reasonable precision based on the input parameters.

