The sample mean \(\bar{X}\) for a random sample of size \(n = 12\) from a uniform distribution on \((0,1)\) has a population mean \(\mu = 0.5\) and population variance \(\sigma^2 = \frac{1}{12}\). By the Central Limit Theorem, \(\bar{X}\) is approximately normally distributed with mean \(\mu_{\bar{X}} = 0.5\) and variance \(\sigma_{\bar{X}}^2 = \frac{\sigma^2}{n} = \frac{1/12}{12} = \frac{1}{144}\), so the standard deviation is \(\sigma_{\bar{X}} = \frac{1}{12}\).

The probability \(P(0.5 \leq \bar{X} \leq \frac{2}{3})\) is approximated using the standard normal distribution. The standardized bounds are:
- Lower bound: \(z_{\text{lower}} = \frac{0.5 - 0.5}{1/12} = 0\)
- Upper bound: \(z_{\text{upper}} = \frac{\frac{2}{3} - 0.5}{1/12} = \frac{\frac{1}{6}}{1/12} = 2\)

Thus, \(P(0.5 \leq \bar{X} \leq \frac{2}{3}) = P(0 \leq Z \leq 2)\), where \(Z\) is a standard normal variable. This probability is \(\Phi(2) - \Phi(0)\), where \(\Phi\) is the cumulative distribution function of the standard normal distribution. Using standard values, \(\Phi(2) \approx 0.97725\) and \(\Phi(0) = 0.5\), so:
\[
P(0 \leq Z \leq 2) = 0.97725 - 0.5 = 0.47725
\]
Rounded to three significant figures, the result is 0.477.

