* RESPONSE 1 *
**************
The energy of one mole of photons is calculated using the formula \(E = \frac{N_A h c}{\lambda}\), where \(N_A\) is Avogadro's number (\(6.022 \times 10^{23} \, \text{mol}^{-1}\)), \(h\) is Planck's constant (\(6.626 \times 10^{-34} \, \text{J·s}\)), \(c\) is the speed of light (\(3.00 \times 10^8 \, \text{m/s}\)), and \(\lambda\) is the wavelength in meters.

Convert the wavelength from nanometers to meters: \(\lambda = 300 \, \text{nm} = 300 \times 10^{-9} \, \text{m} = 3.00 \times 10^{-7} \, \text{m}\).

Substitute the values:  
\[ E = \frac{(6.022 \times 10^{23}) \times (6.626 \times 10^{-34}) \times (3.00 \times 10^8)}{3.00 \times 10^{-7}} \]

First, compute the numerator:  
\( (6.022 \times 10^{23}) \times (6.626 \times 10^{-34}) = 3.990 \times 10^{-10} \)  
Then multiply by \(c\):  
\( 3.990 \times 10^{-10} \times 3.00 \times 10^8 = 1.197 \times 10^{-1} \, \text{J·m/mol} \)  

Now divide by \(\lambda\):  
\[ E = \frac{1.197 \times 10^{-1}}{3.00 \times 10^{-7}} = 3.990 \times 10^5 \, \text{J/mol} \]

Convert to kJ/mol (since \(1 \, \text{kJ} = 1000 \, \text{J}\)):  
\[ E = \frac{3.990 \times 10^5}{1000} = 399 \, \text{kJ/mol} \]

The wavelength \(300 \, \text{nm}\) has three significant figures, so the result is rounded to three significant figures, giving \(399 \, \text{kJ/mol}\).

This energy (\(399 \, \text{kJ/mol}\)) is very close to the typical single-bond energy of \(400 \, \text{kJ/mol}\), indicating that UV photons of this wavelength have sufficient energy to break such bonds.

