The dissociation energy \( D_e \) is calculated from the given \( D_0 \), \( \omega_e \), and \( \omega_e x_e \) using the formula accounting for zero-point energy (ZPE) with anharmonic correction:

\[ D_e = D_0 + \text{ZPE} \]

where the ZPE is given by:

\[ \text{ZPE} = h c \left( \frac{1}{2} \omega_e - \frac{1}{4} \omega_e x_e \right) \]

Given:
- \( D_0 = 2.4287 \, \text{eV} \)
- \( \omega_e = 1405.65 \, \text{cm}^{-1} \)
- \( \omega_e x_e = 23.20 \, \text{cm}^{-1} \)

