- Lower bound: \(z_{\text{lower}} = \frac{0.5 - 0.5}{1/12} = 0\)
- Upper bound: \(z_{\text{upper}} = \frac{\frac{2}{3} - 0.5}{1/12} = \frac{\frac{1}{6}}{1/12} = 2\)

Thus, \(P(0.5 \leq \bar{X} \leq \frac{2}{3}) = P(0 \leq Z \leq 2)\), where \(Z\) is a standard normal variable. This probability is \(\Phi(2) - \Phi(0)\), where \(\Phi\) is the cumulative distribution function of the standard normal distribution. Using standard values, \(\Phi(2) \approx 0.97725\) and \(\Phi(0) = 0.5\), so:
\[
