Problem: 5.3-15. Three drugs are being tested for use as the treatment of a certain disease. Let $p_1, p_2$, and $p_3$ represent the probabilities of success for the respective drugs. As three patients come in, each is given one of the drugs in a random order. After $n=10$ "triples" and assuming independence, compute the probability that the maximum number of successes with one of the drugs exceeds eight if, in fact, $p_1=p_2=p_3=0.7$
 The unit of the answer should be  .
Solution: The probability that the maximum number of successes with one of the drugs exceeds eight is calculated as follows. Each drug has a success probability of 0.7 and is tested in 10 independent trials. The number of successes for each drug follows a binomial distribution with parameters \(n = 10\) and \(p = 0.7\).

The probability that a single drug has more than 8 successes (i.e., 9 or 10 successes) is:
- \(P(S_i = 10) = (0.7)^{10} \approx 0.0282475249\)
- \(P(S_i = 9) = \binom{10}{9} (0.7)^9 (0.3) = 10 \times (0.7)^9 \times 0.3 \approx 0.121060821\)
- \(P(S_i > 8) = P(S_i = 9) + P(S_i = 10) \approx 0.121060821 + 0.0282475249 = 0.1493083459\)

The probability that a single drug has at most 8 successes is:
- \(P(S_i \leq 8) = 1 - P(S_i > 8) \approx 1 - 0.1493083459 = 0.8506916541\)

Since the drugs are independent, the probability that all three drugs have at most 8 successes is:
- \(P(\text{all } S_i \leq 8) = [P(S_i \leq 8)]^3 \approx (0.8506916541)^3 \approx 0.615625381\)

The probability that the maximum number of successes exceeds eight is the complement:
- \(P(\max > 8) = 1 - P(\text{all } S_i \leq 8) \approx 1 - 0.615625381 = 0.384374619\)

